{ This is an attempt to lessen the punch of e5, but concedes having to put the Bishop on e2 instead of d3 von Fishellini,Rufus: 'This is White's only serious attempt after 7. b3 because it prevents the generally desirable e6-e5 break. Still, it is not as active a square as d3 and Black has some time to get his pieces out before White can threaten e3-e4.' }
8... b6 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. O-O Qe7
{ This seems like the easiest solution. Black puts his Queen on a nice centralized square and prevents e3-e4 from being comfortably achieved due to the availability of the f7-f5 tactic. A good rule of thumb for Black is to use his Rooks to follow White's. If White plays Rfd1 and Rac1, Black should play Rfd8 and Rac8. Similarly, if White goes for Rad1 and Rfe1  (which I believe is his best plan)  , Black should play Rad8 and Rfe8. }
11. Rad1 Rad8 { As mentioned, Black should follow White's Rooks. } 12. e4
{ Again, White is not ready for this advance just yet. } 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4
