Rfe8
{ This is the most critical position of the variation, and White has a few things he can try. e3-e4 now makes much more sense than before because the Rook is placed better on e1, or White can try to transfer his Bishop to g2. In general, whenever White plays g2-g3, Black can often respond with Bd6-b4. The point is that he doesn't normally want to trade the Bishop for the Knight, but if White weakens the long diagonal and the light squares around his King, then swapping Bxc3 and getting c6-c5 through becomes much more dangerous. }
13. Bf1
{ I believe this is White's most dangerous attempt. e6-e5 is romantic, but in the modern era, seems not to hold up very well. Black is best advised to instead accept hanging pawns. }
13... c5
{ Normally I am very hesitant to accept hanging pawns, but under the circumstances, I think it is the best choice. White is ready to expand with e3-e4 soon, and Black gets a fantastic version of the hanging pawns position, for 2 reasons. First, all the minor pieces are still on the board, and second, White's Rooks are now misplaced. They would much prefer to be on d1 and c1! So, In order to 'force' Black into the hanging pawns position, White needed to put his Rooks on d1 and e1 to threaten e4, but now that he got the hanging pawns, they are not coordinating well.   13...e5?!  14.dxe5!  A prudent move that gives White a small edge.   14.cxd5  This move, which the computers initially recommend, is met with a beautiful refutation:  14...e4!  15.dxc6  Otherwise Black takes back cxd5 with a fantastic position.  exf3  16.cxb7  Bxh2!  17.Kxh2  Qd6  18.Kh3  And now a move from outer space...  Re5!!  19.dxe5  The threat of Re5-h5 is decisive, and the Rook is immune.  19...Qe6  20.Kh2  Qxe5  21.g3  Qh5  22.Kg1  Ng4  White is mated. But he can avoid such a fate if he knows to take on e5 instead of d5.  14...Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Bxe5  16.cxd5  cxd5  17.Nb5+=  I reached this position in a blitz game against Ding Liren in the Speed Chess Championship. I held a draw, but the position is a little uncomfortable thanks to the isolated d-pawn and passive b7-Bishop. }
14. cxd5 exd5 15. dxc5 bxc5
{ The evaluation of this position is critical for the line, as it is one of White's most challenging tries. I think Black is okay and can hope to launch a Kingside attack while always checking to see if the d5-d4 break will work, but future tests will be needed to see if this is correct or not. Stockfish does share my point of view and evaluates the position as equal. }
