{ In practice, almost all human games have continued with White choosing to castle Queenside. This is unsurprising, as castling short could walk into a quick h5-h4, but I actually believe going Kingside is the more challenging option that puts Black under the most pressure. White's best plan to break down Black's position is b4-b5, which obviously will be much harder to pull off if the King is sitting on c1. In addition, the open h-file might look nice, but it is entirely useless because as mentioned, Black will also castle long if White does, and the Bishop on g7 defending the pawn on h6 defending the pawn on g5 means the h-file will stay closed forever. }
12... Nb6 13. O-O-O Be6
{ As mentioned, Black castles the same side as White. Stockfish initially is excited about White's prospects, but quickly calms down. }
14. Kb1 Qe7 15. Na4 O-O-O 16. Rc1 Kb8
{ The last important move. Black is ready to tuck his Bishop away on c8 to keep his King totally secure, and will slowly but surely aim to open the Kingside with h5-h4. The machines call the position a tiny bit better for White, but I don't buy it at all. The Bishop pair may someday count, Black has a clear plan of action, and no major weaknesses. His results in human play have been excellent. }
