{ This is the second most common move and recommended in Williams' course, but it is also extremely cooperative and White is already worse. }
4... Bb4
{ White is already facing direct threats against the c3-Knight, and should watch out for Nf6-e4. He has no good way to complete his development. }
5. Bd3 { Following along with Williams' proposed repertoire. } 5... c5
{ Here we see why the Knight on c3 is so awkward. White cannot complete his development with either Nf3 or Nge2 on account of c4, when the Bishop on d3 either gets trapped or has to allow a devastating Nf6-e4. }
6. dxc5 { A sad necessity. } 6... Nbd7
{ The c5-pawn isn't going anywhere, and Black remains flexible. If White develops his Knight to f3, it will be worth it to shatter the Queenside pawn structure, but if he develops the Knight to e2, then Black can take with the Bishop on c5 to make sure he gets e6-e5 in. }
