{ This move is very popular at all levels, thanks in no small part to the efforts of Boris Avrukh, who recommended it in his original Grandmaster Repertoire book back in 2008, and doubled down on recommending it again when he released a revised second version in 2016. In general, I consider his 1. d4 repertoire books to be the gold standard of club level preparation, and it is the most challenging 1. d4 repertoire for Black players to face. I've even played this line a few times myself, essentially just copying the books. Luckily though, I was able to find a chapter where I could find a move order on that he did not consider seriously enough. This is a very conceptual line where move orders are extremely important. So, while there are no super long variations, it is critical to remember exactly when to play each move. }
5... Bb4+ 6. Nbd2
{ Avrukh only seriously considers this move order, which I believe is inaccurate. }
6... Ne4 7. a3 Bd6 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Be2
{ This is the crux of Avrukh's plan. Rather than automatically putting the Bishop on d3, he instead puts it on e2. As a result, White will be able to play the typical stonewall regrouping with O-O and Ne1-d3, and then perhaps Nf3-e5. Once this happens he will expel the active Knight on e4 by means of f2-f3, and I think White has every chance to fight for an advantage. The whole point of Black's play is to launch a Kingside attack, and this is very dependent on White being unable to plant a Knight on e5, which I believe he will manage to do here. }
