{ Despite the position looking very similar to that after Bc4-e2, the position is remarkably different. It is similar in that Black wants the same c6-c5 break while White should look for e3-e4, but once e3-e4 happens and Black responds with e6-e5, White's plan changes. He will generally take twice on e5 and play h3 to overprotect the g4 square, and then follow up with Bc1-e3 and eventually f2-f4. This is helped a lot by the Bishop on d3, which supports the potentially vulnerable e4-pawn after the inevitable Rf8-e8. By contrast, the previously most dangerous plans of taking dxe5 and then aiming to follow up with Nf3-d4 or Nf3-h4 are now totally senseless due to the hanging Bishop on d3. In addition, White can often play Nf3-g5 with a gain of tempo due to the hanging pawn on h7 in order to get to e4 quickly to try to stop the c6-c5 break. This would not work with the Bishop on e2 as h7 would not be hanging. As such, despite the very minor change to the position, play takes on a very different flavor. }
10... Bb7
{ Black plays in the same manner as he does against Bc4-e2, at least for now. However, here he does not have a choice since Nc3-e4 was a serious threat. }
11. a3
{ This is the main move by far, and can also come from an Open Meran move order with 6. Bd3 instead of 6. Qc2. White would like to play b2-b4 if given the opportunity, and in the meantime, he has prevented Black from playing b5-b4 himelf. One of the biggest appeals is that Black is unable to play my intended Qd8-b8, which I do against 11. a3 in the 10. Be2 line, because h7 will be hanging at the end. }
11... Rc8
{ I like the most direct move best, as I am worried about White's aforementioned plan to play e3-e4, h2-h3, take everything on e4 and put the Bishop on e3. By making a very direct move, Black's play is extremely obvious and he wants c6-c5 sooner rather than later. In fact, he can play it next move even with the b5-pawn hanging thanks to tactical energy on the c-file. White's only serious attempt at an advantage is to enter the chaos with Ng5. }
12. b4
{ This move attempts to prevent the c6-c5 break and is consistent with a2-a3, but Black is fine. }
12... c5
{ This surprising advance was first played by Kasimdzhanov and earned him an easy draw against Topalov, although I believe Black should advance a7-a5 instead. It has since become an enormous battleground, with the main line running }
13. bxc5 Bxf3 14. cxd6 Nd5 15. gxf3 Qg5+ 16. Kh1 Qh5
{ The position is very complicated, but I don't trust it for Black. We'll see why 12...a5 first is an improvement. }
