1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5
{ Classically speaking, I believe this is White's most ambitious move. Black has played both e7-e6 and c7-c6, which disturbs the development of both his light-squared Bishop and the b8-Knight. The reason the line is strategically sound is that the threat of d5xc4 is very real, which encourages White to either play e2-e3 to box in his own Queen's Bishop  (as we see in the Meran)  or take on d5, which lets the c8-Bishop run free. By playing Bc1-g5, White is trying to call Black's bluff about taking on c4, and then develop with e2-e3 next, with perfect coordination. Historically, Black has mostly looked into the very sharp lines following d5xc4, either directly  (the Botvinnik Variation)  or after a preliminary h7-g6  (the Moscow Variation)  . But the third option, 5... Nbd7, has largely been frowned upon since it allows White to develop his c1-Bishop outside the pawn chain without losing the c4-pawn. However, I feel this is unjust, as we will soon see. }
5... Nbd7 6. cxd5
{ Taking on d5 now is a much more serious attempt to fight for an edge than it was on the previous move because now Black's Knight stands on d7. As such, he will not be able to get his Bishop to f5 before White gets his own Bishop to d3. As mentioned, if Black can take over the f5-b1 diagonal in the Carlsbad structures, he is nearly always fine, but in this position, he will be unable to do so, and has to look for another plan connected with grabbing the Bishop pair. The move is implicitly mentioned as the main recommendation in Larry Kaufman's 2012 repertoire with the implication that it will soon transpose to the standard Queen's Gambit Declined, but as we will see, this will not be the case, so anyone who follows that repertoire will not find it useful against what I am recommending. }
6... exd5
{ This transposes directly to a Carlsbad QGD where White has already committed the Knight to f3 }
7. e3
{ This is the only move White ever tries. His development scheme is simple- Bf1-d3, Qd1-c2, and O-O. If Black plays normally, he will likely end up slightly worse. But I want to change the character of the game completely. }
7... h6 { Black chases the Bishop. } 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nh5
{ It is very important to note that chasing the Bishop in this manner only works because White has already taken on d5. Black has a clear plan for all of his pieces- take on g3, Bf8-g7, Nd7-b6, and most importantly, Bc8-e6. That last part is of the utmost importance. If the pawns on c4 and e6 were still present, Black would not be able to develop his Queen's Bishop. }
10. Bd3 Nxg3 11. hxg3 Bg7
{ A good rule of thumb for Black here is to castle whichever direction White castles in. Opposite side castling leads to more dynamic positions where the presence of weaknesses  (such as the slightly overextended h6+g5 pawn chain)  can really become a big deal, while same-side castling positions tend to be calmer and favor more long term assets, such as the Bishop pair. }
12. O-O
{ I actually think the best try is to castle short. Black now should also castle short because if he leaves the King in the center, the e3-e4 break could really hurt. }
12... Nb6
{ White now has to be a bit careful. Black could play h5-h4 if he is too slow. }
13. Qc2 { A strong move. White prepares for hostilities in the center. } 13...
O-O
{ If Black is allowed to play a7-a5 next, I really can't imagine him ever being worse. White will be unable to set his minority attack in motion and has no other decent plan since e3-e4 will only leave him with an isolani now that Black's King is out of the center. }
14. b4 { As such, I view the immediate b4 as White's only critical move. }
14... Qe7
{ Black needs to be sure he is ready to meet b4-b5 with c6-c5. This will leave him with an isolani, but also a monstrously strong and unopposed Bishop on g7. I think he is fine here, as I cannot see how White gets b4-b5 in without allowing c6-c5 in response. From Black's end, he will follow up with Bc8-e6, Ra8-c8, and eventually can look for counterplay with f7-f5 or even h5-h4. }
15. b5 c5 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Rac1 Be6
{ If Black's Bishop on g7 were exchanged for any of White's minor pieces, Black would be much worse. As is, he clearly has enough counterplay, and his King has no worries despite the loosened pawn cover. }
